
     <p>2025.12.4 : <a href="https://ndpr.nd.edu/reviews/conceptualising-concepts-in-greek-philosophy/" >View this Review Online</a> | <a href="https://ndpr.nd.edu//news" >View Recent NDPR Reviews</a></p>
     <p><strong><p><strong>Gábor Betegh and Voula Tsouna, (eds.). <em>Conceptualising Concepts in Greek Philosophy</em>, Cambridge University Press, 2024, 506pp., $150.00 (hbk) ISBN 9781009369571. </strong></p></strong></p>
     <p><strong>Reviewed by Christoph Helmig, University of Cologne</strong></p>
     <p>Although scholars regularly refer to the language of concepts and preconceptions when discussing ancient and late ancient texts, there are not many contributions that explicitly focus on the nature and character of these terms, their Greek or Latin equivalents, and their philosophical implications. The book under review is of interest to those working on ancient epistemology, theories of knowledge acquisition, concept formation, and mental entities in general.</p> <p>The selection of texts and authors discussed range from the Presocratics to Greek Neoplatonism and the early fathers of the Church. As may be expected, there is a certain focus on Plato, Aristotle, and Hellenistic philosophy, but we also find more diachronic contributions on ‘relative concepts’ (M. Duncombe) and ‘concepts in Greek mathematics’ (R. Netz), as well as...
